Class ProbFunTree<T>

  • java.lang.Object
    • markov.ProbFunTree<T>
  • Type Parameters:
    T - The type of the elements that will be picked from

    public class ProbFunTree<T>
extends java.lang.Object
    A class where a set of elements are picked from randomly to decide the next element that will be the output of fun() based on the previously returned elements.
    Since:
    Copyright 2020
    Author:
    Alexander Johnston

    • Constructor Detail

      • ProbFunTree

        public ProbFunTree(java.util.Set<T> choices,
                   int layers)
        Creates a ProbFunTree where there is an equal chance of getting any element from choices when fun() in called. Note that the elements in choices passed into this constructor will NOT be copied and will be added by reference.
        Parameters:
        choices - as the choices to be randomly picked from.
        layers - as the number of layers for this ProbFunTree to generate. Ex: for choices[0, 1] and layers=2, the following data structure will be made, [[0->0.5][1->0.5]] and [[0->[[0->0.5][1->0.5]]][1->[[0->0.5][1->0.5]]]].
        Throws:
        java.lang.NullPointerException - if choices is null.
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if there aren't at least two elements in choices or layers is not at least 1.

    • Method Detail

      • clearProbs

        public void clearProbs()
        Sets the probabilities to there being an equal chance of getting any element from this ProbFunTree

      • clearHistory

        public void clearHistory()
        Clears the history, but not the probabilities, so the next generation is way more likely to produce favorable results after good() or bad() have been called one or more times. Due to propagation of past values, history may not produce favorable results.

      • addToAll

        public void addToAll(T element)
        Adds an element to the parent and all it's children in this ProbFunTree, making the probability equal to 1.0/n where n is the number of elements contained in this ProbFunTree.
        Parameters:
        element - as the element to add to the parent and all it's children.
        Throws:
        java.lang.NullPointerException - if element is null.

      • addToAll

        public void addToAll(T element,
                     double percent)
        Adds an element to the parent and all it's children in this ProbFunTree with the specified probability.
        Parameters:
        element - as the element to add to the parent and all it's children.
        percent - between 0 and 1 exclusive, as the chance of the parent and all it's children of this ProbFunTree returning element.
        Throws:
        java.lang.NullPointerException - if element is null.
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if percent is not between 0.0 and 1.0 (exclusive).

      • removeFromAll

        public void removeFromAll(T element)
        Removes an element from the parent and it's children in this ProbFunTree. If an node in the tree has only 2 elements, then element will not be removed that that specific node.
        Parameters:
        element - as the element to remove from the parent and it's children in this ProbFunTree.
        Throws:
        java.lang.NullPointerException - if element is null.

      • purgeAll

        public void purgeAll()
        Removes elements with the lowest probabilities in this ProbFunTree. If a node has two elements, no elements will be removed. If a node has two elements after a removal, no more elements will be removed.

      • purgeAll

        public void purgeAll(double percent)
        Removes elements with probabilities less than or equal to percent of being generated from this ProbFunTree. If a node has two elements, no elements will be removed. If a node has two elements after a removal, no more elements will be removed.
        Parameters:
        percent - as the upper limit, inclusive, of the probability of elements being returned to be removed from this ProbFunTree.
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if percent is not between 0.0 and 1.0 (exclusive)

      • good

        public void good(java.util.List<T> elements,
                 double percent)
        Adjust the probabilities to make the elements more likely to be returned when fun() is called in the order they appear in elements.
        Parameters:
        elements - as the elements to make appear more often in the order they should appear in.
        percent - as the percentage between 0 and 1 (exclusive), of the probabilities of getting the elements to add to the probabilities.
        Throws:
        java.lang.NullPointerException - if elements is null.
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if the percent isn't between 0 and 1 exclusive or elements is empty.

      • bad

        public void bad(java.util.List<T> elements,
                double percent)
        Adjust the probabilities to make the elements less likely to be returned when fun() is called in the order they appear in elements.
        Parameters:
        elements - as the elements to make appear less often in the order they should not appear in.
        percent - as the percentage between 0 and 1 (exclusive), of the probabilities of getting the elements to subtract from the probabilities.
        Throws:
        java.lang.NullPointerException - if elements is null.
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if the percent isn't between 0 and 1 exclusive or elements is empty.
